## Background and Motivation

I'm currently trying to implement a specification that requires me to validate a Multipart form. 
Previously I was using `FormFeature` to do the parsing, but since I need to validate the order of boundaries, this is not optimal, since I first have to read the entire form, before I can validate the order.

So I attempted to replicate the behavior of [`FormFeature.InnerReadForm`](https://github.com/dotnet/aspnetcore/blob/c925f99cddac0df90ed0bc4a07ecda6b054a0b02/src/Http/Http/src/Features/FormFeature.cs#L146) in a way that suits my use case. 
I was able to recreate everything I needed except for the [`EnableRewind`](https://github.com/dotnet/aspnetcore/blob/c925f99cddac0df90ed0bc4a07ecda6b054a0b02/src/Http/Http/src/Features/FormFeature.cs#L209) call on the `MultipartSection`.
In order to replicate this in my code, I would have to copy over some internal code, which is really none of my business.

For the `HttpRequest` the needed internal `BufferingHelper` is exposed via [`HttpRequestRewindExtension`](https://github.com/dotnet/aspnetcore/blob/c925f99cddac0df90ed0bc4a07ecda6b054a0b02/src/Http/Http/src/Extensions/HttpRequestRewindExtensions.cs), but it isn't exposed for the `MultipartSection`.

## Proposed API

```diff
namespace Microsoft.AspNetCore.Http
{
+     public static class MultipartSectionRewindExtensions
+     {
+         public static void EnableBuffering(this MultipartSection section);
+ 
+         public static void EnableBuffering(this MultipartSection section, int bufferThreshold);
+ 
+         public static void EnableBuffering(this MultipartSection section, long bufferLimit);
+ 
+         public static void EnableBuffering(this MultipartSection section, int bufferThreshold, long bufferLimit);
+     }
}
```

## Usage Examples

```csharp
// ...

var reader = new MultipartReader(boundary, httpRequest.Body);
var options = new FormOptions();

var section = await reader.ReadNextSectionAsync(cancellationToken);

// if it is a file section we could now enable buffering for it:
section.EnableBuffering(httpRequest.HttpContext.Response.RegisterForDispose, 
    options.MemoryBufferThreshold, options.MultipartBodyLengthLimit);

// ...
```

## Alternative Designs

I wanted to keep it as similar as possible to the `HttpRequest`, so I haven't thought about alternative designs.

## Risks

None to my knowledge.

